2026-06-09 16:23:12,618 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Actual-Close Basis: Months of FY2025 Inclusion\n\nSpaceX\'s fiscal year ends December 31, so FY2025 runs from **January 1, 2025 to December 31, 2025**.\n\n### X Holdings (X)\n- **Merger effective date:** March 28, 2025 (xAI acquired X Holdings Corp.)\n- **Actual-close inclusion in FY2025:** X Holdings was included in the xAI consolidated entity from March 28 through December 31, 2025 — approximately **9 months** of FY2025 (278 days, or ~9.1 months). It was standalone for the first ~3 months of FY2025 (January 1 – March 27).\n- **Inclusion in SpaceX:** X Holdings was **never** directly part of SpaceX during FY2025 on an actual-close basis, because xAI itself did not merge into SpaceX until February 2, 2026.\n\n### xAI\n- **Merger effective date:** February 2, 2026 (SpaceX acquired X.AI Holdings Corp.)\n- **Actual-close inclusion in FY2025:** xAI was included in SpaceX for **0 months** of FY2025. The merger closed after FY2025 ended entirely.\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Entity | Actual-Close Months in FY2025 (within SpaceX consolidated) | Recast Months in FY2025 |\n|---|---|---|\n| SpaceX (standalone) | 12 months | 12 months |\n| xAI | **0 months** | 12 months (recast) |\n| X Holdings | **0 months** (within SpaceX); ~9 months (within xAI) | 12 months (recast) |\n\n---\n\n## Analytical Challenge Created by Retrospective Recast Accounting\n\nThe retrospective recast under common-control accounting creates a fundamental **disconnect between reported financials and actual economic integration timing**. The key analytical challenges are:\n\n### 1. Phantom Full-Year Combination\nThe recast financials present SpaceX, xAI, and X Holdings as a single consolidated entity for **all 12 months of FY2025** — and indeed for all historical periods presented. In reality, neither xAI nor X Holdings was legally part of SpaceX during any month of FY2025. The FY2025 consolidated revenue, expenses, and cash flows therefore reflect a combined entity that did not actually exist during that period.\n\n### 2. Loss of Standalone Visibility\nBecause the recast constitutes a "change in reporting entity," **separate financial statements for xAI and X are not provided**. Analysts cannot evaluate the standalone historical financial health, cash flows, or operational margins of the individual predecessor entities prior to the mergers. This is particularly significant given the vastly different business models (aerospace, AI/LLM, and social media/advertising).\n\n### 3. Distorted Period-over-Period Comparisons\nYear-over-year growth rates and trend analyses are unreliable because the degree of "fictional" combination varies by period. For example, FY2024 recast financials show all three entities combined for 12 months, yet none were legally combined at any point during that year. The recast numbers embed intercompany eliminations of historical related-party transactions that would not have been eliminated in the standalone entities\' actual financials.\n\n### 4. Inconsistent Equity Treatment\nWhile common stock is retrospectively recast on an as-converted basis for all periods, **xAI\'s Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock is NOT recast** for periods prior to February 2, 2026. This creates a structural break in the historical comparability of the capital structure — the balance sheet shows preferred stock in its original legal form for prior periods, but common stock as if already converted.\n\n### 5. No Goodwill or Step-Up in Basis\nThe common-control accounting means net assets are carried at **historical carrying amounts** with no goodwill or intangible asset recognition. This understates the economic consideration that would have been paid in an arm\'s-length transaction and eliminates the amortization/depreciation step-ups that would normally accompany a business combination, potentially inflating reported post-merger profitability relative to a fair-value acquisition.\n\n### 6. Audit Complexity\nThe auditor\'s report is **dual-dated** — March 30, 2026 for the base financials, but **May 7, 2026** for the effects of the common-control reorganization, stock split, and segment realignment — indicating that the retrospective recast required significant additional audit procedures and judgment beyond standard fieldwork.\n\n**Bottom line:** No period in the S-1 reflects standalone SpaceX operations. Every historical figure is a recast combination of entities that were legally and operationally separate for significant portions of the periods presented, making it analytically hazardous to draw conclusions about organic growth, margin trends, or capital efficiency without disaggregating the segment-level data (Space, Connectivity, AI) with caution.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
